<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Saxifraga tolmiei </i>grows in open mats with stems 10-20 cm tall. The leaves are dark green, clustered, and fleshy. The white flowers with red pistils extend above the plant mat. Plants produce extensive rhizomes. <i>S. tolmiei </i>is mainly a plant of the Pacific Northwest and Rocky Mountains. In California, it occurs in the Klamath Mountains, Cascades, and Sierra Nevada at subalpine and alpine elevations. Stands are local in extent at highest elevations near late-season snow beds. Stands occupy similar environments to those of the <i>Carex helleri, Ericameria discoidea-Hulsea algida, </i>and <i>Oxyria digyna </i>alliances (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands of <i>Saxifraga tolmiei-Luzula divaricata</i> association at Harvey Monroe Hall RNA (Taylor 1984, see Cheng 2004) and at Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) in the Sierra Nevada (M261Eo) are associated with steep, rocky slopes in sheltered locations. Similar stands dominated by <i>Saxifraga tolmiei</i> occur on granitic rocks in the Russian Peak Wilderness, Trinity Alps, and other ranges in the Klamath Mountains (M261A). <i>Luetkea pectinata</i> is another Cascadian species that grows with <i>S. tolmiei</i> in the Klamath Mountains and Southern Cascades (M261D) in California. We need more sampling and analysis to understand the relationships of sparsely vegetated herbaceous types at alpine elevations in the state. </div>
</div>

	

    
